"{\n    \"analysis\": \"The data shows a clear increasing trend in the number of days above 100 degrees Fahrenheit over the years. There are some fluctuations year to year, but the overall trend is upwards.\",\n    \"risks\": \"The increasing number of days above 100 degrees Fahrenheit poses significant risks to human health, agriculture, and infrastructure. Heatwaves can lead to heat-related illnesses and deaths, crop failures, and strain on energy resources for cooling.\",\n    \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Promote energy-efficient cooling solutions such as reflective roofing, shade trees, and efficient air conditioning systems to reduce energy consumption during heatwaves.\",\n        \"Encourage property owners to plant drought-resistant and heat-tolerant landscaping to reduce water usage and maintain green spaces.\",\n        \"Provide education and resources on heat safety measures such as staying hydrated, limiting outdoor activities during peak heat hours, and checking on vulnerable populations like the elderly.\",\n        \"Invest in green infrastructure projects such as urban heat island mitigation strategies, green roofs, and permeable pavements to reduce the urban heat island effect in cities.\",\n        \"Develop and update emergency response plans for extreme heat events, including cooling centers, outreach to vulnerable communities, and coordination with local health departments.\"\n    ]\n}"